Issues.Body:
### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

forms

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

Considering this code:

```
constructor( private _fb: FormBuilder) {}

ngOnInit() {
  this.form = this._fb.group<{name: FormControl<string|null>}>({
    name: new FormControl(null),
  });
  
  // Below code should throw error but not.
  this.form.controls.name.setValue(1234); 
}
```

**Expected**: the form field `name` should be typed as `string` or `null`, and should show error when setting its value to any other types.
**Actual**:   `this.form.controls.name.setValue(1234);` succeed without any warnings

### Please provide the environment you discovered this bug in (run `ng version`)

Angular: 14.0.2
IDE: VS Code

### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

compiler

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

If we pass the property whose type contains only falsy types to the `*ngIf` directive:

```ts
@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  template: `
    <p *ngIf="falsy as f">
      <!-- no compilation errors -->
      <app-child [str]="f"></app-child>
      <app-child [str]="falsy"></app-child>
    </p>
  `,
  standalone: true,
  imports: [CommonModule, ChildComponent],
})
export class AppComponent {
  falsy: false | null | undefined = false;
}

@Component({
  selector: 'app-child',
  template: '{{ str }}',
  standalone: true,
})
export class ChildComponent {
  @Input() str = '';
}
```

the type of the passed property, as well as its alias, will be `any` within the `*ngIf` template.

Based on the context type guard:

```ts
static ngTemplateContextGuard<T>(
  dir: NgIf<T>, ctx: any
): ctx is NgIfContext<Exclude<T, false | 0 | '' | null | undefined>> {
  return true;
}
```

I expected the type to be `never`.

### Please provide a link to a minimal reproduction of the bug

https://github.com/markostanimirovic/ng-if-falsy-types

